FILTER(REGEX( ?terms_labels, ""Raman spectroscopy"")) } "	nit (English text): Raman spectroscopy is a type of spectroscopy that uses a high-power laser to measure the absorption spectrum of light by molecules. It is a useful analytical tool for the rapid, low-cost determination of molecular composition, identifying molecular structures and bonding information. Raman spectroscopy works by measuring the inelastic light scattering that occurs when photons are absorbed by molecules, creating a molecule's distinctive vibrational spectrum. Converting photons to scattered photons in a process called inelastic scattering, Raman spectroscopy identifies and distinguishes specific vibrational bands (called Raman bands) from molecules of various types. Thus, Raman spectroscopy offers great potential as a fast, low-cost tool for studying organic molecules. Raman spectroscopy has been used to characterize biological and organic materials such as pharmaceutical products, polymers, cosmetics, and food products. It has also been utilized to determine the structure and composition of airborne particulates, and to analyze environmental samples such as soil and water. The atomic nucleus (nucleus) of an atom is composed of a proton and neutron, two types of particles that are identical to each other.
